# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: taints-tolerations
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance specifically refers to a system's capability to handle faults without any degradation or downtime.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] In the event of an error, end-users remain unaware of any issues.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Conversely, a system that experiences errors with some interruption in service or graceful degradation of performance is termed 'resilient'.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] In resilience, the system adapts to the error, maintaining service but acknowledging a certain impact on performance.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Typically, fault tolerance describes computer systems, ensuring the overall system remains functional despite hardware or software issues.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Non-computing examples include structures that retain their integrity despite damage from fatigue, corrosion or impact.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The first known fault-tolerant computer was SAPO, built in 1951 in Czechoslovakia by Antonín Svoboda.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Its basic design was magnetic drums connected via relays, with a voting method of memory error detection (triple modular redundancy).
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Several other machines were developed along this line, mostly for military use.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Computers with a high amount of runtime that would be under heavy use, such as many of the supercomputers used by insurance companies for their probability monitoring.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Most of the development in the so-called LLNM (Long Life, No Maintenance) computing was done by NASA during the 1960s, in preparation for Project Apollo and other research aspects.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] NASA's first machine went into a space observatory, and their second attempt, the JSTAR computer, was used in Voyager.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] This computer had a backup of memory arrays to use memory recovery methods and thus it was called the Jet Propulsion Laboratory Self-Testing-And-Repairing computer.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] It could detect its own errors and fix them or use redundant modules as needed.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The computer is still working, as of early 2022.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Hyper-dependable computers were pioneered mostly by aircraft manufacturers, nuclear power companies, and the railroad industry in the United States.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] These entities needed computers with massive amounts of uptime that would fail gracefully enough during a fault to allow continued operation, while relying on constant human monitoring of computer output to detect faults.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] IBM developed the first computer of this kind for NASA for guidance of Saturn V rockets.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Later, BNSF, Unisys, and General Electric built their own.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] In the 1970s, much work happened in the field.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] For instance, F14 CADC had built-in self-test and redundancy.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] In general, the early efforts at fault-tolerant designs were focused mainly on internal diagnosis, where a fault would indicate something was failing and a worker could replace it.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] SAPO, for instance, had a method by which faulty memory drums would emit a noise before failure.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Later efforts showed that to be fully effective, the system had to be self-repairing and diagnosing – isolating a fault and then implementing a redundant backup while alerting a need for repair.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] This is known as N-model redundancy, where faults cause automatic fail-safes and a warning to the operator, and it is still the most common form of level one fault-tolerant design in use today.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Voting was another initial method, as discussed above, with multiple redundant backups operating constantly and checking each other's results.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] For example, if four components reported an answer of 5 and one component reported an answer of 6, the other four would "vote" that the fifth component was faulty and have it taken out of service.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] This is called M out of N majority voting.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Historically, the trend has been to move away from N-model and toward M out of N, as the complexity of systems and the difficulty of ensuring the transitive state from fault-negative to fault-positive did not disrupt operations.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers, in 1976 and Stratus Technologies were among the first companies specializing in the design of fault-tolerant computer systems for online transaction processing.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Hardware fault tolerance sometimes requires that broken parts be removed and replaced with new parts while the system is still operational (in computing known as *hot swapping*).
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Such a system implemented with a single backup is known as **single point tolerant** and represents the vast majority of fault-tolerant systems.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] In such systems the mean time between failures should be long enough for the operators to have sufficient time to fix the broken devices (mean time to repair) before the backup also fails.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] It is helpful if the time between failures is as long as possible, but this is not specifically required in a fault-tolerant system.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance is notably successful in computer applications.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers built their entire business on such machines, which used single-point tolerance to create their NonStop systems with uptimes measured in years.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Fail-safe architectures may encompass also the computer software, for example by process replication.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Data formats may also be designed to degrade gracefully.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Hyper Text Markup Language (HTML) for example, is designed to be forward compatible, allowing Web browsers to ignore new and unsupported HTML entities without causing the document to be unusable.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Additionally, proper user interface design mandates that websites provide an optional lightweight front end that does not rely on JavaScript and has a minimal layout, to ensure wide accessibility and outreach.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] A highly fault-tolerant system might continue at the same level of performance even though one or more components have failed.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] For example, a building with a backup electrical generator will provide the same voltage to wall outlets even if the grid power fails.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] A system that is designed to fail safe, or fail-secure, or **fail gracefully**, whether it functions at a reduced level or fails completely, does so in a way that protects people, property, or data from injury, damage, intrusion, or disclosure.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] In computers, a program might fail-safe by executing a graceful exit (as opposed to an uncontrolled crash) to prevent data corruption after an error occurs.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] A similar distinction is made between "failing well" and "failing badly".
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] A system designed to experience **graceful degradation**, or to **fail soft** (used in computing, similar to "fail safe") operates at a reduced level of performance after some component fails.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] For example, if grid power fails, a building may operate lighting at reduced levels or elevators at reduced speeds.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] In computing, if insufficient network bandwidth is available to stream an online video, a lower-resolution version might be streamed in place of the high-resolution version.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Progressive enhancement is another example, where web pages are available in a basic functional format for older, small-screen, or limited-capability web browsers, but in an enhanced version for browsers capable of handling additional technologies or that have a larger display.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] In fault-tolerant computer systems, programs that are considered robust are designed to continue operation despite an error, exception, or invalid input, instead of failing completely.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Software brittleness is the opposite of robustness.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Resilient networks continue to transmit data despite the failure of some links or nodes.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Resilient buildings and infrastructure are likewise expected to prevent complete failure in situations like earthquakes, floods, or collisions.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] A system with high failure transparency will alert users that a component failure has occurred, even if it continues to operate with full performance, so that failure can be repaired or imminent complete failure anticipated.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Likewise, a fail-fast component is designed to report at the first point of failure, rather than generating reports when downstream components fail.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] This allows easier diagnosis of the underlying problem, and may prevent improper operation in a broken state.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] A **single fault condition** is a situation where one means for protection against a hazard is defective.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] If a single fault condition results unavoidably in another single fault condition, the two failures are considered one single fault condition.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Providing fault-tolerant design for every component is normally not an option.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Associated redundancy brings a number of penalties: increase in weight, size, power consumption, cost, as well as time to design, verify, and test.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] An example of a component that passes all the tests is a car's occupant restraint system.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] While the *primary* occupant restraint system is not normally thought of, it is gravity.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] If the vehicle rolls over or undergoes severe g-forces, then this primary method of occupant restraint may fail.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Restraining the occupants during such an accident is absolutely critical to safety, so the first test is passed.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Accidents causing occupant ejection were quite common before seat belts, so the second test is passed.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The cost of a redundant restraint method like seat belts is quite low, both economically and in terms of weight and space, so the third test is passed.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Therefore, adding seat belts to all vehicles is an excellent idea.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Other "supplemental restraint systems", such as airbags, are more expensive and so pass that test by a smaller margin.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] It would also be prohibitively costly to further double-up the main components and they would add considerable weight.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] However, the similarly critical systems for actuating the brakes under driver control are inherently less robust, generally using a cable (which can rust, stretch, jam, or snap) or hydraulic fluid (which can leak, boil and develop bubbles, or absorb water and thus lose effectiveness).
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The cumulatively unlikely combination of total foot brake failure with the need for harsh braking in an emergency will likely result in a collision, but still one at lower speed than would otherwise have been the case.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] In comparison with the foot pedal activated service brake, the parking brake itself is a less critical item, and unless it is being used as a one-time backup for the footbrake, will not cause immediate danger if it is found to be nonfunctional at the moment of application.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, on shallow gradients, the transmission can be shifted into Park, Reverse or First gear, and the transmission lock / engine compression used to hold it stationary, as there is no need for them to include the sophistication to first bring the vehicle to a halt.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] On motorcycles, a similar level of fail-safety is provided by simpler methods; first, the front and rear brake systems are entirely separate, regardless of their method of activation (that can be cable, rod or hydraulic), allowing one system to fail entirely while leaving the other unaffected.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Fault isolation to the failing component – When a failure occurs, the system must be able to isolate the failure to the offending component.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] This requires the addition of dedicated failure detection mechanisms that exist only for the purpose of fault isolation.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Recovery from a fault condition requires classifying the fault or failing component.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Faults are commonly categorized by their locality (internal or external to the system), cause (natural or human-made), duration (permanent or transient), and effect on system behavior.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Fault containment to prevent propagation of the failure – Some failure mechanisms can cause a system to fail by propagating the failure to the rest of the system.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] An example of this kind of failure is the "rogue transmitter" that can swamp legitimate communication in a system and cause overall system failure.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Firewalls or other mechanisms that isolate a rogue transmitter or failing component to protect the system are required.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Availability of reversion modes, which is the abandonment of recent changes, usually to software, that bring a system back to reasonably proper behavior and function.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] In addition, fault-tolerant systems are characterized in terms of both planned service outages and unplanned service outages.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] These are usually measured at the application level and not just at a hardware level.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The figure of merit is called availability and is expressed as a percentage.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] For example, a five nines system would statistically provide 99.999% availability.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Fault-tolerant systems are typically based on the concept of redundancy.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Research into the kinds of tolerances needed for critical systems involves a large amount of interdisciplinary work.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The more complex the system, the more carefully all possible interactions have to be considered and prepared for.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] All implementations of RAID, redundant array of independent disks, except RAID 0, are examples of a fault-tolerant storage device that uses data redundancy.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] A lockstep fault-tolerant machine uses replicated elements operating in parallel.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] At any time, all the replications of each element should be in the same state.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The same inputs are provided to each replication, and the same outputs are expected.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The outputs of the replications are compared using a voting circuit.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] A machine with two replications of each element is termed dual modular redundant (DMR).
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can then only detect a mismatch and recovery relies on other methods.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] A machine with three replications of each element is termed triple modular redundant (TMR).
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can determine which replication is in error when a two-to-one vote is observed.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] In this case, the voting circuit can output the correct result, and discard the erroneous version.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] After this, the internal state of the erroneous replication is assumed to be different from that of the other two, and the voting circuit can switch to a DMR mode.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] This model can be applied to any larger number of replications.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Lockstep fault-tolerant machines are most easily made fully synchronous, with each gate of each replication making the same state transition on the same edge of the clock, and the clocks to the replications being exactly in phase.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] However, it is possible to build lockstep systems without this requirement.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Bringing the replications into synchrony requires making their internal stored states the same.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] They can be started from a fixed initial state, such as the reset state.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, the internal state of one replica can be copied to another replica.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] One variant of DMR is **pair-and-spare**.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Two replicated elements operate in lockstep as a pair, with a voting circuit that detects any mismatch between their operations and outputs a signal indicating that there is an error.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Another pair operates exactly the same way.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] A final circuit selects the output of the pair that does not proclaim that it is in error.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Pair-and-spare requires four replicas rather than the three of TMR, but has been used commercially.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The approach has performance costs: because the technique rewrites code to insert dynamic checks for address validity, execution time will increase by 80% to 500%.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Recovery shepherding is a lightweight technique to enable software programs to recover from otherwise fatal errors such as null pointer dereference and divide by zero.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Comparing to the failure oblivious computing technique, recovery shepherding works on the compiled program binary directly and does not need to recompile to program.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] It uses the just-in-time binary instrumentation framework Pin.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] It attaches to the application process when an error occurs, repairs the execution, tracks the repair effects as the execution continues, contains the repair effects within the application process, and detaches from the process after all repair effects are flushed from the process state.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] It does not interfere with the normal execution of the program and therefore incurs negligible overhead.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] For 17 of 18 systematically collected real world null-dereference and divide-by-zero errors, a prototype implementation enables the application to continue to execute to provide acceptable output and service to its users on the error-triggering inputs.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The circuit breaker design pattern is a technique to avoid catastrophic failures in distributed systems.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Redundancy is the provision of functional capabilities that would be unnecessary in a fault-free environment.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] This can consist of backup components that automatically "kick in" if one component fails.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] For example, large cargo trucks can lose a tire without any major consequences.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] They have many tires, and no one tire is critical (with the exception of the front tires, which are used to steer, but generally carry less load, each and in total, than the other four to 16, so are less likely to fail).
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The idea of incorporating redundancy in order to improve the reliability of a system was pioneered by John von Neumann in the 1950s.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Two kinds of redundancy are possible: space redundancy and time redundancy.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy provides additional components, functions, or data items that are unnecessary for fault-free operation.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy is further classified into hardware, software and information redundancy, depending on the type of redundant resources added to the system.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] In time redundancy the computation or data transmission is repeated and the result is compared to a stored copy of the previous result.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] The current terminology for this kind of testing is referred to as In Service Fault Tolerance Testing or ISFTT for short.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] There is a difference between fault tolerance and systems that rarely have problems.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] For instance, the Western Electric crossbar systems had failure rates of two hours per forty years, and therefore were highly *fault resistant*.
[src:taints-tolerations/fault-tolerance] But when a fault did occur, they stopped operating completely, and therefore were not *fault tolerant*.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:taints-tolerations/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
