[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Hosted applications: From the 1990s traditional application service providers (ASPs) hosted (then-existing) applications on behalf of their customers.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Depending on the limitation of the underlying application, ASPs were forced to host applications on separate machines (if multiple instances of the applications could not be executed in the same physical machine) or as separate processes.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Multitenant applications represent a more mature architecture which enables a similar service with lower operational cost.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Web applications: Popular consumer-oriented web applications (such as Hotmail) developed with a single application instance serving all customers.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Multitenant applications represent a natural evolution from this model, offering additional customization to groups of users within (say) the same client organization.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] In a multitenancy environment, multiple customers share the same application, running on the same operating system, on the same hardware, with the same data-storage mechanism.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] The distinction between the customers is achieved during application design, so that customers do not share or see each other's data.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] This contrasts with virtualization, where components are transformed so that each customer application appears to run on a separate virtual machine.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] This is attractive because redesigning an application for multitenancy can be costly, particularly for software vendors who also continue to offer an on-premises single-tenant version of their product and would otherwise have to maintain two distinct products.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] When applications are repackaged as virtual appliances, the same appliance image can be deployed in ISV-hosted, on-premises, or trusted-third-party locations, and migrated from one deployment site to another over time.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Multitenancy allows for cost savings over and above the basic economies of scale achievable from consolidating IT resources into a single operation.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] An application instance usually incurs a certain amount of memory and processing overhead which can be substantial when multiplied by many customers, especially if the customers are small.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Multitenancy reduces this overhead by spreading it over many customers.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Further cost savings may come from licensing costs of the underlying software (such as operating systems and database management systems).
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Put crudely, if you can run everything on a single software instance, you only have to buy one software license.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] In addition, development of multitenant systems is more complex, and security testing is more stringent because multiple customers' data is being commingled.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Because of the additional customization complexity and the need to maintain per-tenant metadata, multitenant applications require a larger development effort.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Considerations such as how tenant data is partitioned, how per-tenant schema extensions are stored, and how shared resources are isolated must be taken into account.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Multitenancy simplifies the release management process.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] In a traditional release management process, packages containing code and database changes are distributed to client desktop and/or server machines; in the single-instance case, this would be one server machine per customer.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] These packages then have to be installed on each individual machine.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] With the multitenant model, the package typically only needs to be installed on a single server.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] This greatly simplifies the release management process, and the scale is no longer dependent on the number of customers.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] At the same time, multitenancy increases the risks and impacts inherent in applying a new release version.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] As there is a single software instance serving multiple tenants, an update on this instance may cause downtime for all tenants even if the update is requested and useful for only one tenant.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Also, some bugs and issues resulted from applying the new release could manifest in other tenants' personalized view of the application.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Because of possible downtime, the moment of applying the release may be restricted depending on time usage schedule of more than one tenant.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] A central design decision in a multitenant application is how each tenant's data is isolated within shared storage.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] When tenants share compute, storage, or network resources, a single tenant generating disproportionate load can degrade performance for others, a condition known as the "noisy neighbor" problem.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Mitigations include per-tenant rate limiting, resource quotas, and isolating high-demand tenants onto dedicated resources.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] According to Marc Brooker, in a multi tenant architecture, unrelated and uncorrelated workloads should be grouped together.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] That's because mixing different workloads, with different needs and patterns, hide the patterns of each workload.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Grouping workloads reduces the peak-to-average ratio of the overall system; individual workloads can utilize more resources during peak times without significantly increasing the overall cost structure of the system and subsequently helps you to achieve more cost efficiency.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Note that multiple workloads from the same application, customer or industry, tend to behave as a single workload.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Multitenant applications are typically required to provide a high degree of customization to support each target organization's needs.
[src:taints-tolerations/multitenancy] Multitenant applications are expected to provide adequate security, robustness and performance between multiple tenants which is provided by the layers below the application in case of multi-instance applications.
[src:taints-tolerations/orchestration-computing] In system administration, **orchestration** is the automated configuration, coordination, deployment, and management of computer systems and software.
[src:taints-tolerations/orchestration-computing] Many tools exist for automating server configuration and management.
[src:taints-tolerations/orchestration-computing] Orchestration is often discussed in the context of service-oriented architecture, virtualization, provisioning, converged infrastructure, and dynamic data center topics.
[src:taints-tolerations/orchestration-computing] Orchestration in this sense is about aligning the business request with the applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:taints-tolerations/orchestration-computing] In the context of cloud computing, the main difference between workflow automation and orchestration is that workflows are processed and completed as processes within a single domain for automation purposes.
[src:taints-tolerations/orchestration-computing] Orchestration, meanwhile, incorporates workflows and provides a directed action towards larger goals and objectives.
[src:taints-tolerations/orchestration-computing] In the context of application programming interfaces (APIs), API orchestration refers to the process of integrating multiple APIs into a unified system to streamline workflows and enhance user experience.
[src:taints-tolerations/orchestration-computing] The approach coordinates the flow of data, the execution sequence, and the dependencies among different APIs to achieve a defined business objective.
[src:taints-tolerations/orchestration-computing] API orchestration is commonly applied in environments that utilize microservices architectures or legacy systems, where the interaction of several APIs is required to complete a task.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] In computer programming, **resource management** refers to techniques for managing resources (components with limited availability).
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Computer programs may manage their own resources by using features exposed by programming languages (Elder, Jackson & Liblit (2008) is a survey article contrasting different approaches), or may elect to manage them by a host – an operating system or virtual machine – or another program.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Host-based management is known as *resource tracking,* and consists of cleaning up resource leaks: terminating access to resources that have been acquired but not released after use.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This is known as *reclaiming* resources, and is analogous to garbage collection for memory.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] On many systems, the operating system reclaims resources after the process makes the exit system call.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] The omission of releasing a resource when a program has finished using it is known as a resource leak, and is an issue in sequential computing.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Multiple processes wish to access a limited resource can be an issue in concurrent computing, and is known as resource contention.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Resource management seeks to control access in order to prevent both of these situations.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Formally, resource management (preventing resource leaks) consists of ensuring that a resource is released if and only if it is successfully acquired.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This general problem can be abstracted as "*before,* *body,* and *after*" code, which normally are executed in this order, with the condition that the *after* code is called if and only if the *before* code successfully completes, regardless of whether the *body* code executes successfully or not.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This is also known as *execute around* or a *code sandwich,* and occurs in various other contexts, such as a temporary change of program state, or tracing entry and exit into a subroutine.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] However, resource management is the most commonly cited application.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] In aspect-oriented programming, such execute around logic is a form of *advice*.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] In the terminology of control flow analysis, resource release must postdominate successful resource acquisition; failure to ensure this is a bug, and a code path that violates this condition causes a resource leak.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks are often minor problems, generally not crashing the program, but instead causing some slowdown to the program or the overall system.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] However, they may cause crashes – either the program itself or other programs – due to *resource exhaustion:* if the system runs out of resources, acquisition requests fail.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This can present a security bug if an attack can cause resource exhaustion.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks may happen under regular program flow – such as simply forgetting to release a resource – or only in exceptional circumstances, such as when a resource is not released if there is an exception in another part of the program.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks are very frequently caused by early exit from a subroutine, either by a `return` statement, or an exception raised either by the subroutine itself, or a deeper subroutine that it calls.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] While resource release due to return statements can be handled by carefully releasing within the subroutine before the return, exceptions cannot be handled without some additional language facility that guarantees that release code is executed.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] More subtly, successful resource acquisition must dominate resource release, as otherwise the code will try to release a resource it has not acquired.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] The consequences of such an incorrect release range from being silently ignored to crashing the program or unpredictable behavior.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] These bugs generally manifest rarely, as they require resource allocation to first fail, which is generally an exceptional case.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Further, the consequences may not be serious, as the program may already be crashing due to failure to acquire an essential resource.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] However, these can prevent recovery from the failure, or turn an orderly shutdown into a disorderly shutdown.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] In computer science, resource contention refers to a conflict that arises when multiple entities attempt to access a shared resource, like random access memory, disk storage, cache memory, internal buses, or external network devices.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Memory can be treated as a resource, but memory management is usually considered separately, primarily because memory allocation and deallocation is significantly more frequent than acquisition and release of other resources, such as file handles.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Memory managed by an *external* system has similarities to both (internal) memory management (since it is memory) and resource management (since it is managed by an external system).
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Examples include memory managed via native code and used from Java (via Java Native Interface); and objects in the Document Object Model (DOM), used from JavaScript.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] In both these cases, the memory manager (garbage collector) of the runtime environment (virtual machine) is unable to manage the external memory (there is no shared memory management), and thus the external memory is treated as a resource, and managed analogously.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] However, cycles between systems (JavaScript referring to the DOM, referring back to JavaScript) can make management difficult or impossible.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Lexical management, when applicable, allows a better separation of concerns and is less error-prone.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This is correct if the intervening `...` code does not contain an early exit (`return`), the language does not have exceptions, and `open` is guaranteed to succeed.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] However, it causes a resource leak if there is a return or exception, and causes an incorrect release of unacquired resource if `open` can fail.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] There are two more fundamental problems: the acquisition-release pair is not adjacent (the release code must be written far from the acquisition code), and resource management is not encapsulated – the programmer must manually ensure that they are always paired.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] In combination, these mean that acquisition and release must be explicitly paired, but cannot be placed together, thus making it easy for these to not be paired correctly.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This ensures correct release even if there is a return within the body or an exception thrown.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Further, note that the acquisition occurs *before* the `try` clause, ensuring that the `finally` clause is only executed if the `open` code succeeds (without throwing an exception), assuming that "no exception" means "success" (as is the case for `open` in Python).
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] While this ensures correct resource management, it fails to provide adjacency or encapsulation.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] There are many variations in the implementation, and there are also significantly different approaches.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] The most common approach to resource management across languages is to use unwind protection, which is called when execution exits a scope – by execution running off the end of the block, returning from within the block, or an exception being thrown.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This works for stack-managed resources, and is implemented in many languages, including C#, Common Lisp, Java, Python, Ruby, and Scheme.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] The main problems with this approach is that the release code (most commonly in a `finally` clause) may be very distant from the acquisition code (it lacks *adjacency*), and that the acquisition and release code must always be paired by the caller (it lacks *encapsulation*).
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] An alternative, more imperative approach, is to write asynchronous code in direct style: acquire a resource, and then in the next line have a *deferred* release, which is called when the scope is exited – synchronous acquisition followed by asynchronous release.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This originated in C++ as the ScopeGuard class, by Andrei Alexandrescu and Petru Marginean in 2000, with improvements by Joshua Lehrer, and has direct language support in D via the `scope` keyword (ScopeGuardStatement), where it is one approach to exception safety, in addition to RAII (see below).
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] It has also been included in Go, as the `defer` statement.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This approach lacks encapsulation – one must explicitly match acquisition and release – but avoids having to create an object for each resource (code-wise, avoid writing a class for each type of resource).
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] In object-oriented programming, resources are encapsulated within objects that use them, such as a `file` object having a field whose value is a file descriptor (or more general file handle).
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This allows the object to use and manage the resource without users of the object needing to do so.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] However, there is a wide variety of ways that objects and resources can be related.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Firstly, there is the question of ownership: does an object *have* a resource?
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Most common is to acquire a resource during object creation, and then explicitly release it via an instance method, commonly called `dispose`.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This is analogous to traditional file management (acquire during `open`, release by explicit `close`), and is known as the dispose pattern.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This is the basic approach used in several major modern object-oriented languages, including Java, C# and Python, and these languages have additional constructs to automate resource management.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] However, even in these languages, more complex object relationships result in more complex resource management, as discussed below.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] A natural approach is to make holding a resource be a class invariant: resources are acquired during object creation (specifically initialization), and released during object destruction (specifically finalization).
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This is known as Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII), and ties resource management to object lifetime, ensuring that live objects have all necessary resources.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Other approaches do not make holding the resource a class invariant, and thus objects may not have necessary resources (because they've not been acquired yet, have already been released, or are being managed externally), resulting in errors such as trying to read from a closed file.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This approach ties resource management to memory management (specifically object management), so if there are no memory leaks (no object leaks), there are no resource leaks.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] RAII works naturally for heap-managed resources, not only stack-managed resources, and is composable: resources held by objects in arbitrarily complicated relationships (a complicated object graph) are released transparently simply by object destruction (so long as this is done properly!).
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Firstly, because resources are expensive, it is desirable to release them promptly, so objects holding resources should be destroyed as soon as they become garbage (are no longer in use).
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] However, most modern automatic memory management is non-deterministic, making no guarantees that objects will be destroyed promptly or even at all!
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This is because it is cheaper to leave some garbage allocated than to precisely collect each object immediately on its becoming garbage.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Secondly, releasing resources during object destruction means that an object must have a *finalizer* (in deterministic memory management known as a *destructor*) – the object cannot simply be deallocated – which significantly complicates and slows garbage collection.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] When multiple objects rely on a single resource, resource management can be complicated.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] A fundamental question is whether a "has a" relationship is one of *owning* another object (object composition), or *viewing* another object (object aggregation).
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] A common case is when one two objects are chained, as in pipe and filter pattern, the delegation pattern, the decorator pattern, or the adapter pattern.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] If the second object (which is not used directly) holds a resource, is the first object (which is used directly) responsible for managing the resource?
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This is generally answered identically to whether the first object *owns* the second object: if so, then the owning object is also responsible for resource management ("having a resource" is transitive), while if not, then it is not.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Further, a single object may "have" several other objects, owning some and viewing others.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Both cases are commonly found, and conventions differ.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] In object aggregation, nothing needs to be done by the viewing object, as it is not responsible for the resource.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] For example, in the Java Class Library, `Reader#close()` closes the underlying stream, and these can be chained.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] For example, a `BufferedReader` may contain a `InputStreamReader`, which in turn contains a `FileInputStream`, and calling `close` on the `BufferedReader` in turn closes the `InputStreamReader`, which in turn closes the `FileInputStream`, which in turn releases the system file resource.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] By contrast, in Python, a csv.reader does not own the `file` that it is reading, so there is no need (and it is not possible) to close the reader, and instead the `file` itself must be closed.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] Various mechanisms exist to allow greater control of resource management.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] For example, in the Google Closure Library, the `goog.Disposable` class provides a `registerDisposable` method to register other objects to be disposed with this object, together with various lower-level instance and class methods to manage disposal.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] In structured programming, stack resource management is done simply by nesting code sufficiently to handle all cases.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This requires only a single return at the end of the code, and can result in heavily nested code if many resources must be acquired, which is considered an anti-pattern by some – the *Arrow Anti Pattern,* due to the triangular shape from the successive nesting.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] One other approach, which allows early return but consolidates cleanup in one place, is to have a single exit return of a function, preceded by cleanup code, and to use goto to jump to the cleanup before exit.
[src:taints-tolerations/resource-management-computing] This is infrequently seen in modern code, but occurs in some uses of C.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:taints-tolerations/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] Taints and tolerations work together to ensure that pods are not scheduled onto inappropriate nodes.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] One or more taints are applied to a node; this marks that the node should not accept any pods that do not tolerate the taints.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] You add a taint to a node using kubectl taint.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The taint has key `key1`, value `value1`, and taint effect `NoSchedule`.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] This means that no pod will be able to schedule onto `node1` unless it has a matching toleration.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] You specify a toleration for a pod in the PodSpec.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The default Kubernetes scheduler takes taints and tolerations into account when selecting a node to run a particular Pod.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] However, if you manually specify the `.spec.nodeName` for a Pod, that action bypasses the scheduler; the Pod is then bound onto the node where you assigned it, even if there are `NoSchedule` taints on that node that you selected.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] If this happens and the node also has a `NoExecute` taint set, the kubelet will eject the Pod unless there is an appropriate tolerance set.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The default value for `operator` is `Equal`.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] If the `key` is empty, then the `operator` must be `Exists`, which matches all keys and values.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] Note that the `effect` still needs to be matched at the same time.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] An empty `effect` matches all effects with key `key1`.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The above example used the `effect` of `NoSchedule`.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] Alternatively, you can use the `effect` of `PreferNoSchedule`.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] No new Pods will be scheduled on the tainted node unless they have a matching toleration.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] to avoid placing a Pod that does not tolerate the taint on the node, but it is not guaranteed.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] You can put multiple taints on the same node and multiple tolerations on the same pod.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The way Kubernetes processes multiple taints and tolerations is like a filter: start with all of a node's taints, then ignore the ones for which the pod has a matching toleration; the remaining un-ignored taints have the indicated effects on the pod.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] In this case, the pod will not be able to schedule onto the node, because there is no toleration matching the third taint.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] But it will be able to continue running if it is already running on the node when the taint is added, because the third taint is the only one of the three that is not tolerated by the pod.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] Normally, if a taint with effect `NoExecute` is added to a node, then any pods that do not tolerate the taint will be evicted immediately, and pods that do tolerate the taint will never be evicted.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] However, a toleration with `NoExecute` effect can specify an optional `tolerationSeconds` field that dictates how long the pod will stay bound to the node after the taint is added.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] means that if this pod is running and a matching taint is added to the node, then the pod will stay bound to the node for 3600 seconds, and then be evicted.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] If the taint is removed before that time, the pod will not be evicted.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] In addition to `Equal` and `Exists`, you can use numeric comparison operators (`Gt` and `Lt`) to match taints with integer values.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] This is useful for threshold-based scheduling, such as matching nodes by reliability level or SLA tier.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] For numeric operators, both the toleration and taint values must be valid integers.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] If either value cannot be parsed as an integer, the toleration does not match.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] tolerations operators, the API server validates that the toleration values are valid integers.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] Taint values on nodes are not validated at node registration time.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] ), pods with numeric comparison operators will not match that taint and cannot schedule on that node.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] This toleration matches the taint on `node1` because `950 > 900` (the taint value is greater than the toleration value for the `Gt` operator).
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] Taints and tolerations are a flexible way to steer pods *away* from nodes or evict pods that shouldn't be running.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The node controller automatically taints a Node when certain conditions are true.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] In case a node is to be drained, the node controller or the kubelet adds relevant taints with `NoExecute` effect.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] This effect is added by default for the `node.kubernetes.io/not-ready` and `node.kubernetes.io/unreachable` taints.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] If the fault condition returns to normal, the kubelet or node controller can remove the relevant taint(s).
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] In some cases when the node is unreachable, the API server is unable to communicate with the kubelet on the node.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The decision to delete the pods cannot be communicated to the kubelet until communication with the API server is re-established.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] In the meantime, the pods that are scheduled for deletion may continue to run on the partitioned node.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The control plane limits the rate of adding new taints to nodes.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] This rate limiting manages the number of evictions that are triggered when many nodes become unreachable at once (for example: if there is a network disruption).
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] You can specify `tolerationSeconds` for a Pod to define how long that Pod stays bound to a failing or unresponsive Node.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] For example, you might want to keep an application with a lot of local state bound to node for a long time in the event of network partition, hoping that the partition will recover and thus the pod eviction can be avoided.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] Kubernetes automatically adds a toleration for `node.kubernetes.io/not-ready` and `node.kubernetes.io/unreachable` with `tolerationSeconds=300`, unless you, or a controller, set those tolerations explicitly.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] These automatically-added tolerations mean that Pods remain bound to Nodes for 5 minutes after one of these problems is detected.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] This ensures that DaemonSet pods are never evicted due to these problems.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The node controller was responsible for adding taints to nodes and evicting pods.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] But after 1.29, the taint-based eviction implementation has been moved out of node controller into a separate, and independent component called taint-eviction-controller.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The control plane, using the node controller, automatically creates taints with a `NoSchedule` effect for node conditions.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The scheduler checks taints, not node conditions, when it makes scheduling decisions.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] This ensures that node conditions don't directly affect scheduling.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] For example, if the `DiskPressure` node condition is active, the control plane adds the `node.kubernetes.io/disk-pressure` taint and does not schedule new pods onto the affected node.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] If the `MemoryPressure` node condition is active, the control plane adds the `node.kubernetes.io/memory-pressure` taint.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] You can ignore node conditions for newly created pods by adding the corresponding Pod tolerations.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The control plane also adds the `node.kubernetes.io/memory-pressure` toleration on pods that have a QoS class other than `BestEffort`.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] This is because Kubernetes treats pods in the `Guaranteed` or `Burstable` QoS classes (even pods with no memory request set) as if they are able to cope with memory pressure, while new `BestEffort` pods are not scheduled onto the affected node.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The DaemonSet controller automatically adds the following `NoSchedule` tolerations to all daemons, to prevent DaemonSets from breaking.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] Adding these tolerations ensures backward compatibility.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] You can also add arbitrary tolerations to DaemonSets.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] Instead of tainting entire nodes, administrators can also taint individual devices when the cluster uses dynamic resource allocation to manage special hardware.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] The advantage is that tainting can be targeted towards exactly the hardware that is faulty or needs maintenance.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] Tolerations are also supported and can be specified when requesting devices.
[src:taints-tolerations/taint-and-toleration] Like taints they apply to all pods which share the same allocated device.
